				<div id="introduction" class="section">
					<h3>Introduction</h3>
					<div id="langmuirMonolayers" class="section">
						<h3>Langmuir Monolayers</h3>
						<p>A Langmuir monolayer is an insoluble layer of amphiphilic molecules at the air-water interface a single molecule thick. Such films are named for Irving Langmuir.  Langmuir and Harkins independently [<a href="#ref1">1</a>,<a href="#ref2">2</a>] demonstrated in 1917 that the films were a single molecule thick and proposed that the polar portion of each molecule pointed towards the water while the non-polar portion pointed away.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-1">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-1	Schematic of a Langmuir Monolayer" href="img/dissertation/monolayerRepresentation.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/monolayerRepresentation.gif" alt="Figure I-1	Schematic of a Langmuir Monolayer" /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-1	Schematic of a Langmuir Monolayer</p>
						</div>
						<p>Not all amphiphilic compounds form Langmuir monolayers. When the attractive intermolecular forces are greater than polar interaction with the water surface the compound will not spread onto the surface.  The compounds used throughout this work are single chain aliphatic compounds or n-alkanoids.  They have a polar head group, a hydrophobic tail, and will be referred to as simple amphiphiles (see <a href="#figI-2">Figure I-2</a>).</p>
						<p>In general compounds with a chain length less than 15 methylene units are soluble in a water subphase while those with greater than 26 do not spread or form lens on a water surface.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-2">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-2	The space filling structure and identification of the head and tail group of compounds used in this work." href="img/dissertation/generalCompoundStructures.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/generalCompoundStructures.gif" alt="Figure I-2	The space filling structure and identification of the head and tail group of compounds used in this work." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-2	The space filling structure and identification of the head and tail group of compounds used in this work.</p>
						</div>
					</div>

					<div id="generalTechniques" class="section">
						<h3>General Techniques</h3>

						<p>Prior to the 1980's, information about monolayer phase behavior was from thermodynamic experiments, surface potential experiments, or theory.</p>
						<p>Thermodynamic experiments were generally conducted by placing a monolayer at a fixed temperature, varying the area available on the surface of the water, and measuring the resulting surface pressure changes.  A plot of the pressure vs. area is called an isotherm.  It is a Π-Area slice through the three-dimensional phase space of Π-Area-Temperature for the compound where Π is the two-dimensional pressure or surface tension.  The slope of this plot is the compressibility and changes in the slope accompany a transition to a new phase or at the coexistence between two phases. Second-order phase transitions appear as kinks in the isotherm while first-order phase transitions or coexistence of two phases appear as flat regions. By conducting several isotherm measurements at different temperatures one can build a larger phase space and plot the generally more useful Π-Temperature diagram</p>
						<p>In surface potential experiments, the monolayer is thought of as conductive plate parallel to the interface. Since amphiphilic are dipolar, variations in collective molecular orientation, which accompany a phase transition, result in different potentials.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-3">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-3	General Isotherm plot showing several basic phases." href="img/dissertation/generalIsothermSmall.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/generalIsothermSmall.gif" alt="Figure I-3	General Isotherm plot showing several basic phases." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-3	General Isotherm plot showing several basic phases.</p>
						</div>
						<p>Early experiments identified four distinct monolayer phases; gas (G), liquid-expanded (LE), liquid-condensed (LC), and solid (S) [<a href="#ref1">1</a>,<a href="#ref2">2</a>].  Later studies by Alexander, Stenhagen, Lundquist, and others found evidence in compressibility measurements that the liquid-condensed phase was in fact many separate phases. [<a href="#ref3">3</a>-<a href="#ref10">10</a>]</p>
						<p>Experiments on Langmuir monolayers generally use a Teflon trough to contain the water and monolayer.  The troughs are often rectangular and made of Teflon to provide a chemically inert and hydrophobic surface. The thermodynamic conditions are set by circulating water through the trough's base and a moving barrier.  The barrier sweeps the surface and changes the area available and thus the two-dimensional pressure.  Different troughs often use varying barrier configurations such as the classic single barrier design shown in <a href="#figI-4">Figure I-4</a>, two barriers with opposing motion, or even circular compression using Teflon bands.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-4">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-4	Schematic of a trough ..." href="img/dissertation/generalTroughDiagram.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/generalTroughDiagram.gif" alt="Figure I-4	Schematic of a trough used to control the thermodynamic conditions of a Langmuir monolayer." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-4	Schematic of a trough used to control the thermodynamic conditions of a Langmuir monolayer.</p>
						</div>
						<p>The pressure is measured using a filter paper Wilhelmy balance.  A monolayer is generally prepared by placing drops of a volatile solution, typically Chloroform, of an amphiphile compound onto the water surface using a micro-syringe. The solvent quickly evaporates and the compound spreads.  The area per molecule is determined by measuring the trough's area, subtracting the area swept by the barrier(s), and then dividing by the known number of molecules deposited. The pressure Π is calculated by Π = Π<sub>0</sub> - Π where Π<sub>o</sub> is the surface tension of pure water and Π is the surface tension of the monolayer-covered water surface.</p>
						<p>The phase behavior of a Langmuir monolayer can be explained by considering a collection of amphiphilic molecules bound to the water surface by their hydrophilic head groups. At low densities, these molecules spread out over the surface and on time average are not in contact with each other. They have a highly disordered structural conformation and both the head groups and tails are in contact with the water surface. This is called the gas phase. As the area is reduced the contact of the molecules is increased, the hydrophobic tails of the compound are no longer in contact with the water surface but are still disordered, and a liquid is formed. This is called the liquid expanded (LE) phase. Both the gas and LE phases are isotropic.  With continued reduction of area the hydrophobic tails must begin to pack largely in an extended all trans conformation, this is the liquid condensed (LC) region.  In the LC region as the area is further reduced, the molecules continue to pack in tighter but distinctly different manners yielding a variety of increasing packed phases.  As the area per molecule is reduced even further the molecules first crystallize, the condensed phase, and then are finally pushed out of the plane of the water surface, the collapsed state.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-5">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-5	Schematic representation of the basic phases of a Langmuir monolayer." href="img/dissertation/monolayerRepresentationOfPhases.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/monolayerRepresentationOfPhases.gif" alt="Figure I-5	Schematic representation of the basic phases of a Langmuir monolayer." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-5	Schematic representation of the basic phases of a Langmuir monolayer.</p>
						</div>
						<p>Isotherm measurements continue to be useful in modern experiments but have limitations.  In general, meticulous technique is required to detect certain phase transitions in the liquid-condensed region.  One particular transition went undetected, the L<sub>2</sub> / Ov transition, until 1993 [<a href="#ref11">11</a>] because both phases have the same area per molecule and compressibility at the phase transition boundary.  In addition, thermodynamic techniques yield no direct molecular or mesophase structural information.</p>
					</div>

					<div id="opticalAndDiffreactionTechniques" class="section">
						<h3>Optical And Diffraction Techniques</h3>
						<p>The invention and application of new techniques such as fluorescence microscopy, Brewster-angle microscopy (BAM), Grazing Incidence X-ray diffraction (GIXD), second harmonic generation spectroscopy [<a href="#ref12">12</a>,<a href="#ref13">13</a>], and Fourier transform infrared reflection-absorption spectroscopy (IRRAS) revealed a wealth of new structural information and provided a basis for this work.  These optical or diffraction techniques, described below, use short wavelength energy that probes the monolayer at smaller, previously inaccessible, length scales.</p>
						<p>Polarized Fluorescence and subsequently Brewster-angle microscopy are primarily sensitive to the tilt orientation of the hydrophobic tail of the molecule.  Unlike IRRAS and GIXD which have signals averaged over macroscopic areas these two techniques allow real space visualization of a monolayer over μm length scales.  These techniques lead to the surprising discovery of mesophases structures on the μm and larger length scales.</p>
						<p>Based upon the work of Beaglehole [<a href="#ref14">14</a>]; Möbius, Overbeck, and Hönig Göttingen [<a href="#ref15">15</a>] and Meunier and Hénon in Paris [<a href="#ref16">16</a>] built the first Brewster-angle microscopes.  When light is reflected from the interface between dielectric media then the polarization of the light is changed.  If the incident light is circularly polarized then the light becomes elliptically polarized and given the dielectric constant one can calculate the thickness of the interface or conversely the dielectric constant from the thickness, this is ellipsometry.  If however one uses light polarized in the incident plane (p-polarized) or perpendicular to the incident plane (s-polarized) the reflectivity varies with the angle of incidence.  For a given surface at a certain angle called the Brewster angle, reflection of p-polarized light is at a minimum.  By placing a polarizing element in the reflected light path that selects only for p-polarization one can remove the contribution of s-polarized light.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-6">
							<a rel="gallery" title="" href="img/dissertation/polarizedLightReflectanceOnWater.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/polarizedLightReflectanceOnWater.gif" alt="Figure I-6	Definition of p- and s- polarized light and the reflective intensity off a surface as a function of incident angle. (Θ&lt;sub&gt;B&lt;/sub&gt; is the Brewster-angle)" /></a>
							<a rel="gallery" title="" href="img/dissertation/definitionOfPAndSPolarization.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/definitionOfPAndSPolarization.gif" alt="Figure I-6	Definition of p- and s- polarized light and the reflective intensity off a surface as a function of incident angle. (Θ&lt;sub&gt;B&lt;/sub&gt; is the Brewster-angle)" /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-6	Definition of p- and s- polarized light and the reflective intensity off a surface as a function of incident angle. (Θ<sub>B</sub> is the Brewster-angle)</p>
						</div>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-7">
