							<a rel="gallery" title="Stepping Stones" href="img/dissertation/steppingStonesLCLECoexistance_3_5_inches.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/steppingStonesLCLECoexistance_3_5_inches.gif" alt="Figure I-7	Examples of textures we have seen by Brewster-angle microscopy.  The field of view is approximately 500µm and the white sizing bar is 100µm." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-7	Examples of textures we have seen by Brewster-angle microscopy.  The field of view is approximately 500µm and the white sizing bar is 100µm.</p>
						</div>
						<p>By changing the nature of the surface interface through the addition of a thin film, as is the case in Langmuir monolayers, the Brewster angle changes and thus the intensity of reflected light at that angle increases.  The now more intense reflected light has a p-polarized component due to the influence of the monolayer.  This reflected light can then be focused onto a camera and one can view differences in contrast due to varying thickness and molecular orientation. For a monolayer of uniform thickness, this allows the experimenter to see optical textures that are related to the molecular orientation.</p>
						<p>Grazing Incidence X-Ray Diffraction is primarily sensitive to intermolecular structure.  By aligning a high intensity source of X-rays in a beam towards a monolayer covered water surface at a grazing angle of approximately 1° and collecting the scattered light one can directly probe the molecular phase structure and obtain information about the various degrees order present.  We will differ a discussion on the analysis of GIXD data until after reviewing the phase diagrams and structure of simple amphiphiles.</p>
						<p>IRRAS produces a spectrum of the monolayer and has only recently been applied to monolayers at the air-water interface [<a href="#ref17">17</a>,<a href="#ref18">18</a>,<a href="#ref19">19</a>].  The technique is particularly sensitive to the displacement of permanent bond dipole moments that yield information about the molecular conformation and head group interactions with the subphase.  IRASS can be used to determine the degree of hydrogen bonding and E/Z conformational structure of the head group.</p>
					</div>

					<div id="phaseDiagrams" class="section">
						<h3>Phase Diagrams</h3>
						<p>Simple amphiphiles like their liquid crystal counterparts have a surprising variety of phases. There are at least 10 different phases, possibly more. Using the nomenclature of Stenhagen, Lunquist [<a href="#ref3">3</a>,<a href="#ref4">4</a>,<a href="#ref8">8</a>-<a href="#ref10">10</a>,<a href="#ref20">20</a>] there are the well documented CS, S, LS, L<sub>2</sub>″, L<sub>2</sub>′, L<sub>2</sub>, Ov, LE, and G phases.  Depending on the chain length and head group, some or all of these phases may be observable in the accessible regions of the phase diagram, <a href="#figI-8">Figure I-8</a>, for a particular amphiphile at any one time. </p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-8">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-8	General phase diagram." href="img/dissertation/phaseDiagramTypeISmall.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/phaseDiagramTypeISmall.gif" alt="Figure I-8	General phase diagram." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-8	General phase diagram.</p>
						</div>
						<p>To first approximation, the head group determines which phases may be observable while the chain length determines how those phases shift in temperature. Long chain lengths will shift the entire diagram right to higher temperatures. Short chain lengths shift the diagram left.  The shift is roughly 6K per methylene unit. So for example, when overlaying the diagrams for octadecanoic acid and heneicosanoic acid, the diagram for heneicosanoic acid would be shifted roughly 15K higher in temperature.</p>
						<p>New phases are being discovered. Recently work by Durbin and Lautz [<a href="#ref21">21</a>,<a href="#ref22">22</a>] has shown that there is an additional intermediate tilt phase, I.  The phase divides the L<sub>2</sub>′ field into the I and L<sub>2</sub>′ phases.</p>
					</div>

					<div id="structuresOfThePhases" class="section">
						<h3>Structure of The Phases</h3>
						<p>The condensed phases (condensed and liquid condensed) have degrees of order not found in the gas and liquid expanded phases. In these phases, the molecular head groups are so closely packed on the interface surface that they form a hexagonal like structure.  The molecular tails are also constrained and adopt an all trans conformation.  One can imagine the resulting variety of phases by considering the possible combinations of head group packing with possible variations in tail tilt, direction, and rotational freedom.  We will define the interface surface or packing plane as the x-y plane, the magnitude of tilt as Θ, and the azimuthal direction of tilt as Φ.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-9">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Definition of molecular axis" href="img/dissertation/molecularOrientation.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/molecularOrientation.gif" alt="Figure I-9	Definition of molecular axis (left) and hexatic axis (right)." /></a>
							<a rel="gallery" title="Definition of heaxtic axis" href="img/dissertation/hexaticAxis.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/hexaticAxis.gif" alt="Figure I-9	Definition of molecular axis (left) and hexatic axis (right)." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-9	Definition of molecular axis (left) and hexatic axis (right).</p>
						</div>



						<p>A useful division drawn from liquid crystal systems classifies the various degrees of order as Bond Orientational Order (BO), Tilt Orientational Order (TO), Positional Order (PO), and Herringbone Order (HO). [<a href="#ref23">23</a>,<a href="#ref24">24</a>,<a href="#ref25">25</a>]  Bond Orientational Order is the degree to which the molecular centers are positioned at a set of fixed angles from each other.  Tilt Orientational Order is the degree of variation of the azimuthal direction of tilt, Φ, under translation.  Positional Order is the degree to which the molecular centers are positioned at equally spaced intervals.  And Herringbone Order is the tail's degree rotational freedom, whether the tails can be modeled as elliptical rods (pack in a herringbone pattern) or as circular rods.  In the isotropic gas and liquid expanded phases none of these orderings is present.</p>
						<p>In the condensed phases BO is always quasi-long range following a power law decay, molecules are positioned along a well-defined angular axis.  This order is what gives rise to the variety of mesophases structures, or textures that persist over length scales of μm.  The axes are called the hexatic axes.</p>
						<p>All the liquid condensed phases also have quasi-long range TO.  There are however differences in the values of Φ.  The tails can either be untilted or tilted with respect to the surface normal resulting in a division between untilted and tilted phases.  The tilted phases have a tilt angle that is dependent on the temperature, pressure, area available, and varies within a phase region.</p>
						<p>Positional Order is either quasi-long range, following a power law decay, or short range, following an exponential decay.  The crystalline phases, CS and L<sub>2</sub>″, have quasi-long range PO.  As opposed to 3-D systems it is possible to have a phase with quasi-long range BO while having short range PO [<a href="#ref26">26</a>,<a href="#ref27">27</a>].  In this cases, the molecules are positioned along well defined axis but do not preserve positional translation along those axis. Phases which have quasi-long range BO, short range PO, and a hexagonal symmetry (a six-fold orientational order) are called hexatic [<a href="#ref26">26</a>,<a href="#ref28">28</a>].  These phases include S, LS, L<sub>2</sub>′, L<sub>2</sub>, and Ov.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-10">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-10	Schematic of nearest neighbor (NN) and next nearest neighbor (NNN) tilt in a condensed phase." href="img/dissertation/neighborDiagram.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/neighborDiagram.gif" alt="Figure I-10	Schematic of nearest neighbor (NN) and next nearest neighbor (NNN) tilt in a condensed phase." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-10	Schematic of nearest neighbor (NN) and next nearest neighbor (NNN) tilt in a condensed phase.</p>
						</div>
						<p>The azimuthal tilt is defined relative to the hexatic axis. In tilted condensed phases Φ is either 0°, 30°, or in the case of the I phase an intermediate value. When <span class="equation">Φ = 0°</span>, the tilt is towards the nearest molecular neighbor and when <span class="equation">Φ = 30°</span>, the tilt is towards the next nearest molecular neighbor.  Phases can therefore be distinguished as nearest neighbor (NN) or next nearest neighbor (NNN) phases, depending on the azimuthal direction of the tilt.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-11">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-11	Schematic of Herringbone Order (HO" href="img/dissertation/herringboneDiagram.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/herringboneDiagram.gif" alt="Figure I-11	Schematic of Herringbone Order (HO)." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-11	Schematic of Herringbone Order (HO).</p>
						</div>
						<p>At higher temperatures and areas the tails are free to rotate and can be effectively modeled as rods. As the temperature or area is reduced, the tail rotation is restricted. The tails in this case can be modeled as elliptical rods and pack in a herringbone pattern. This is referred to as Herringbone Order (HO). This structure can by ordered in one or two dimensions. In a one-dimensional order the row spacing has quasi-long range order but there is only short range translation order within a row. In a two-dimensional crystal, both are quasi-long range.</p>
