						<p>As a result of a Landau theory treatment that has been developed by Kaganer and collaborators, discussed more fully in later chapters, it is conjectured that a line drawn from top to bottom divides the LS and the L<sub>2</sub> phase into the LS<sub>rI</sub>, LS<sub>rII</sub>, L<sub>2d</sub>, and L<sub>2h</sub> phases in Type I compounds or the LS<sub>r1</sub>, LS<sub>r2</sub>, L<sub>2</sub>′, and Ov phases in Type II compounds. To the left of this line there is one-dimensional herringbone order, to the right there is no herringbone order.</p>
					</div>

					<div id="gixdDataAnalysisOfTheCondensedPhases" class="section">
						<h3>GIXD Data Analysis Of The Condensed Phases</h3>
						<p>By aligning a high intensity source of X-rays in a beam towards a monolayer covered water surface at a grazing angle of approximately 1° and collecting the scattered light one can determine the momentum transfer vector K.</p>
						<p>The scattering pattern in reciprocal space is the product of structure factor and the form factor. The structure of a two-dimensional hexagonal lattice in reciprocal space is a set of delta functions along the lines normal to the monolayer plane. These lines are called "Bragg rods". The form factor of an extended chain or long rod is an oblate spheroid. The sphere has values large only along a disk normal to its axis. This is called the reciprocal disk. Their intersection or product gives rise to three pairs of maxima <span class="equation">±K<sub>1</sub>, ±K<sub>2</sub>, ±K<sub>3</sub></span>. These are the six wave vectors of the first-order diffraction peaks.  In the liquid condensed phases, molecules are close packed in a two-dimensional hexatic lattice.  In addition, each molecule is in an all trans conformation so that its chain is structurally similar to a long rod.</p>
						<p>Because the "crystals" in a monolayer are much smaller than the imaging area of the diffraction spot, the signal due to the <span class="equation">K<sub>x</sub></span> and <span class="equation">K<sub>y</sub></span> components are averaged together by <span class="equation">K<sub>xy</sub> = (K<sub>x</sub><sup>2</sup> + K<sub>y</sub><sup>2</sup>)<sup>½</sup></span>. Only the <span class="equation">K<sub>z</sub></span> wave vector is directly measurable.</p>
						<p>For an untilted monolayer in an undistorted lattice, the six wave vectors are degenerate. Only one peak in the scattering pattern will be seen. This degeneracy can be lifted by either distorting the real space unit cell or tilting the real space molecular chains. Distortion alters the <span class="equation">K<sub>x</sub></span> and <span class="equation">K<sub>y</sub></span> wave vectors, while tilting changes the <span class="equation">K<sub>z</sub></span> wave vector.</p>
						<p>Distortion of a liquid condensed phase occurs in one of two ways. If the unit cell is represented by a real space hexagon formed by a close packed structure, then the distance between two opposite molecules in the hexagon can be increased (stretching) or reduced (shrinking). In either case, the scattering pattern in reciprocal space is represented by two distinct peaks. One of which is actually two peaks and degenerate and the other of which is a single peak. The non-degenerate pair of wave vectors is termed <span class="equation">±K<sub>n</sub></span> and the other two pairs of wave vectors are termed <span class="equation">±K<sub>d</sub></span>. When the cell is stretched <span class="equation">|K<sub>n</sub>| &gt; |K<sub>d</sub>|</span>, when the cell is shrunk <span class="equation">|K<sub>n</sub>| &lt; |K<sub>d</sub>|</span>.</p>
						<p>Molecular tilt depends on the magnitude and the direction.  The real space tilt of the molecular chains corresponds to a tilt of the reciprocal disk.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figI-12">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure I-12	Scattering peaks ..." href="img/dissertation/xrayTiltUntiltedSignal.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/xrayTiltUntiltedSignal.gif" alt="Figure I-12	Scattering peaks of: a) Untilted molecules with a hexagonal unit cell and distortion in the NNN direction. B) Tilt and hexagonal unit cell distortion in the NN direction." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure I-12	Scattering peaks of: a) Untilted molecules with a hexagonal unit cell and distortion in the NNN direction. B) Tilt and hexagonal unit cell distortion in the NN direction.</p>
						</div>
						<p>In general, since the intersection of the reciprocal disk and the Bragg rods has three distinct points there are three first-order peaks corresponding to the three wave vector pairs. This is the case in intermediate tilt monolayer phases. If however the tilt is in the direction of one of the Bragg rods there will only be two peaks one of which will be degenerate. This is the case with molecular chains pointed towards NN and NNN. The tilt angle can be directly calculated from the scattering peaks, <span class="equation">tanθ = K<sub>dz</sub> / ( K<sub>dxy</sub><sup>2</sup> - ( K<sub>nxy</sub> / 2 )<sup>2</sup> )<sup>½</sup></span>.</p>
					</div>

				</div>

