				<div id="additionalFindingsAndAnalysisOfLangmuirMonolayersAtEquilibrium" class="section">
					<h3>VII. - Additional Findings and Analysis of Langmuir Monolayers at Equilibrium</h3>
					<div id="AFintroduction" class="section">
						<h3>Introduction</h3>
						<p>The papers that form the preceding chapters form a body of knowledge about the relation between phase diagrams and molecular structure.  In the following chapter, we will highlight aspects of this and make additional comments about the relation between this work and Landau theory analysis.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="AFtypesOfPhaseDiagrams" class="section">
						<h3>Types Of Phase Diagrams</h3>
						<div class="figure" id="figVII-1">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure VII-1	General Type I phase diagram." href="img/dissertation/phaseDiagramTypeISmall.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/phaseDiagramTypeISmall.gif" alt="Figure VII-1	General Type I phase diagram." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure VII-1	General Type I phase diagram.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="table" id="tableVII-A">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Table VII-A	Listed are some compounds used throughout this work." href="img/dissertation/compoundsUsed.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/compoundsUsed.gif" alt="Table VII-A	Listed are some compounds used throughout this work.  The type refers to a general classification system." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Table VII-A	Listed are some compounds used throughout this work.  The type refers to a general classification system.</p>
						</div>

						<p>The study of compounds used throughout this work, <a href="#tableVII-A">Table VII-A</a>, or mixtures of those compounds indicates that a particular compound or mixture has a phase diagram that can be classified as one of two types, or a combination of those two types.  We will refer to those two types as Type I and Type II.</p>
						<p>In general, the acids and acetates have a similar Type I phase diagram, <a href="#figVII-1">Figure VII-1</a>.  This same diagram is qualitatively similar to the diagram for short chain length acids and acetates.  Note that since the pure water subphase freezes at 0°C, and observations more than a few degrees below that temperature are virtually impossible, phases like the CS and L<sub>2</sub>″ are no longer observable.</p>
						<p>We have also made BAM observations of long chain lengths at low temperatures. At these conditions, the system becomes very 'slow' to respond and develops one or several regions of texture rearrangement similar to those seen in other phase transitions inhomogeneously across the surface. Without diffraction experiments, it is unclear if these are slow transitions to a new phase or a type of collapse.</p>
						<p>The alcohols and esters have qualitatively similar diagrams that we refer to as Type II, <a href="#figVII-2">Figure VII-2</a>.</p>

						<div class="figure" id="figVII-2">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure VII-2	General Type II phase diagram." href="img/dissertation/phaseDiagramTypeIISmall.gif"><img src="img/dissertation/phaseDiagramTypeIISmall.gif" alt="Figure VII-2	General Type II phase diagram." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure VII-2	General Type II phase diagram.</p>
						</div>

						<p>The most notable difference between the two types of diagrams is the absence of the L<sub>2</sub> phase.  To first approximation, the two types of diagrams represent the extremes in head group size.  Compounds with effectively large head groups due to purely steric interactions, conformational arrangement, and/or strong hydrogen bonding with the water subphase, exhibit Type I behavior.  While compounds at the other extreme, with effectively small head groups such as alcohols or esters in an E conformation, exhibit Type II behavior.</p>
						<p>Mixtures and monolayers of pure compounds such as the thioic esters and methyl hexadecanoate can exhibit behavior intermediate between these two Types.  Several thioic esters were synthesized which conceptually represented the corresponding acetate with the carbonyl oxygen replaced with sulfur.  This in effect turned off hydrogen bonding and dramatically decreased the effective head group size while slightly increasing the size due to steric interactions.</p>
						<p>One compound studied is not easily assigned one of these two Types or an intermediate, methyl hexadecanoate.  This compound has a phase diagram that looks to be Type II but it has a tilted phase that is NN and not NNN.  Here the high temperature stability of the NN phase is associated with disorder in the chain ends, which plays a larger role in short chain length compounds.  This effect can be seen in other compounds where the stability of the Ov phase and area of the field reduces with decreasing chain length.</p>
						<p>It is likely that these two Types of phases diagrams are not the extreme or only cases.  However, we can order these compounds by their effective head group size based on the point at which the L<sub>2</sub> phase is suppressed by in a mixture of the corresponding acid, a large effective headgroup.</p>

						<div class="table" id="tableVII-B">
							<table>
								<thead>
									<tr><td></td></tr>
								</thead>
								<tbody>
									<tr><td>Acids, Acetates &gt; Thioic Esters &gt; Methyl Esters &gt; Alcohol &gt; Ethyl Ester &gt; Propyl Ester</td></tr>
									<tr><td>Small chain length &gt; Larger chain length</td></tr>
								</tbody>
							</table>
							<p class="caption">Table VII-B	Ordering of effective head group size based on L<sub>2</sub> phase suppression.  Top comparison takes precedence over the lower comparison.</p>
						</div>

						<p>The acids and the acetates are Type I.  The thioic esters are intermediate.  Short chain length methyl esters are intermediate or possibly of a different Type.  Longer chain length methyl esters, other esters, and alcohols are Type II.  To a lesser degree than the head group, chain length increases or decreases the effective head group size.  Long chain lengths with more chain-chain interactions decrease hydrogen bounding.  In the case of the methyl esters chain length is shown to substantially change the phase diagram.</p>
						<p>There are a number of subtleties when comparing these phase diagrams that arise from differences in the compressibility of the head group.</p>
						<p>The phase line from the tilted to the untilted phase is generally at a higher pressure in Type I than in Type II compounds.  The same phase line is at higher pressure with decreasing chain length in Type I compounds.  This is presumably due to a reduced effective head group size as chain-chain interactions reduce hydrogen bonding.</p>
						<p>The magnitude of the temperature shift depends not only on the difference in chain length but on which chain lengths and compounds are in question.  For example, the shift between octadecanoic acid (C18A) and nonadecanoic acid (C19A) is slightly more than the shift between nonadecanoic acid and (C19A) and eicosanoic acid (C20A).</p>
					</div>

					<div id="AFanalysis" class="section">
						<h3>Analysis</h3>
						<p>In the following analysis, our goal is to understand the factors that control the appearance of the non-crystalline NN and NNN tilted phases.  In particular, we know that for pure compounds non-crystalline NN phases have only been found in acids, acetates, thiols, and one ester, methyl hexadecanoate.  The alcohols and all but one ester do not have a non-crystalline NN tilt phase.  We know as well that when we mix a substance that has a NN phases with one that does not, there is a regular change in the phase diagram: the L<sub>2</sub>′/L<sub>2h</sub> boundary moves towards higher T and lower &pi;; the Ov/L<sub>2d</sub> boundary moves towards lower T and lower &pi;; the L<sub>2</sub>′ and Ov phase boundaries eventually touch and the NN phase is driven to zero pressure.</p>
						<p>We see this regular behavior when we keep the chain lengths of the amphiphiles constant but change the head groups, for example when mixing heneicosanoic (C21) acid with heneicosanol.  This suggests that we should be able to understand these phenomena in terms of head group size which may affect properties of the monolayers such as tilt angle or chain packing.</p>
						<p>We can be guided in our analysis by our experiments, by GID studies and by the Landau theory treatment that has been developed by Kaganer and collaborators.  The Landau theory, which is based primarily on the GID studies, seeks to describe the free energy of the monolayer in terms of several order parameters that have been chosen to account for the phase diagram and which satisfy various symmetry conditions.  It is a thermodynamic and not molecular structure.  Kaganer has identified several significant order parameters:</p>
						<p>η = tilt order parameter = sin θ</p>
						<p>ξ = distortion order parameter</p>
						<p>ε<sub>xx</sub> – ε<sub>yy</sub> = ξ cos 2ω</p>
						<p>2 ε<sub>xy</sub> = ξ sin 2ω</p>
						<p>Where <span class="equation">θ</span> is the angle with respect to the surface normal, <span class="equation">ε<sub>ij</sub></span> is the strain tensor, and <span class="equation">ω</span> is the direction of the distortion.</p>
						<p>φ = herringbone order parameter</p>
						<p>h = hexatic order parameter</p>
						<p>h<sub>x</sub> = h cos 6γ</p>
						<p>h<sub>y</sub> = sin 6γ</p>
						<p>Where <span class="equation">φ</span> is the amplitude of a 1-D crystallization wave and <span class="equation">γ</span> is the azimuth of hexatic order.</p>
					</div>

					<div id="AFfreeEnergyInTermsOfOrderParameters" class="section">
						<h3>Free Energy in Terms of Order Parameters</h3>
						<p>The free energy of the monolayer can then be written in terms of a power series in the order parameters including cross terms that represent couplings between them and the phase transitions can be identified by examining minima in the free energy as a function of the order parameters.</p>

						<div class="figure" id="figVII-3">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure VII-3	Highly schematic phase diagram." href="img/dissertation/sketchOfPhaseBoundaries.png"><img src="img/dissertation/sketchOfPhaseBoundariesSmall.png" alt="Figure VII-3	Highly schematic phase diagram." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure VII-3	Highly schematic phase diagram.</p>
						</div>

						<p>Consider the highly schematic boundaries in <a href="#figVII-3">Figure VII-3</a>.  The sequence of transitions R<sub>II</sub> ⇒ Ov ⇒ L<sub>2d</sub> from the untilted hexatic phase R<sub>II</sub> to the NNN tilted hexatic phase Ov to the NN tilted hexatic phase L<sub>2d</sub> is ascribed to the tilt and the coupling between tilt and hexatic order.</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 1)</p>
							<p>Φ<sub>1</sub> = Φ<sub>η</sub> + Φ<sub>ηh</sub> = Aη<sup>2</sup> +Bη<sup>4</sup> – Dhη<sup>6</sup> cos 6(β - γ)	+ Eh<sup>2</sup>η<sup>12</sup> cos 12(β - γ) + Cξ<sup>2</sup> – Vξη<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – ω)</p>
						</div>

						<p>Thermodynamic stability requires <span class="equation">B&gt;0</span>.  It is observed experimentally that the R<sub>II</sub> ⇒ Ov transition is second order.</p>

						<p>When <span class="equation">A&gt;0</span>, Equation 1 gives <span class="equation">η=0</span> and for <span class="equation">A&lt;0, η<sup>2</sup> = -A/2B</span>, so the transition corresponds to <span class="equation">A=0</span>.  The tilt azimuth is determined by the signs of <span class="equation">D</span> and <span class="equation">E</span>.  For <span class="equation">D&gt;0</span> and <span class="equation">E&gt;0</span>, the minimum in <span class="equation">Φ</span> occurs at <span class="equation">β – γ = π/6</span>, correspondingly to NNN tilt.  Thus in the Ov phase <span class="equation">D&lt;0</span> while in L<sub>2d</sub> <span class="equation">D&gt;0</span>.  The transtition Ov ⇒ L<sub>2d</sub> therefore corresponds to <span class="equation">D=0</span>.  It is continuous.  If <span class="equation">E&lt;0</span>, the transition occurs via a phase of intermediate tilt, which we will not consider here.</p>

						<p>As a result of the tilt, there is a distortion in the Ov and L<sub>2d</sub> phases so the free energy must contain a term that arises from this coupling.  To lowest order this is given by</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 2)</p>
							<p>Φ<sub>ηξ</sub> 	= – Vξη<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – ω)</p>
						</div>

						<p>For <span class="equation">V&gt;0</span>, the minimum occurs at <span class="equation">ω = β</span>, which corresponds to distortion in the direction of the tilt; for <span class="equation">V&lt;0</span>, the minimum is at <span class="equation">ω = β + π/2</span> and the distortion is in a direction perpendicular to the tilt.  GID measurements on the Ov and L<sub>2d</sub> phases show that <span class="equation">ω = β</span>, so <span class="equation">V&gt;0</span>.  The term <span class="equation">Cξ<sup>2</sup></span> is <span class="equation">Φ<sub>ξ</sub></span>, the lowest-order term in the free energy associated with the tilt alone.</p>

						<p>Next we consider the transitions S ⇒ L<sub>2</sub>′ ⇒ L<sub>2</sub>, which must include in addition terms involving the herringbone order parameter φ.</p>

						<p>The free energy is then given by:</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 3)</p>
							<p>Φ<sub>2</sub> 	= Φ<sub>1</sub> + Φ<sub>φ</sub> + Φ<sub>φη</sub> + Φ<sub>φξ</sub> + Φ<sub>hφ</sub> = Φ<sub>1</sub> + Fφ<sup>2</sup> + Gφ<sup>4</sup> + Jφ<sup>2</sup>η<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – δ) – uφ<sup>2</sup>ξ cos 2(ω – δ) – Hφ<sup>2</sup>h cos 6(γ – δ)</p>
						</div>

						<p>If <span class="equation">B&lt;0</span>, the free energy expansion in <span class="equation">η<sup>2</sup></span> must include an <span class="equation">η<sup>6</sup></span> term to insure thermodynamic stability.</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 1’)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Aη<sup>2</sup> + Bη<sup>4</sup> + Mη<sup>6</sup></p>
						</div>

						<p>Minimization with respect to <span class="equation">η<sup>2</sup></span> gives:</p>

						<p>When <span class="equation">A=0</span> there are two solutions <span class="equation">η<sup>2</sup> = 0</span> and <span class="equation">η<sup>2</sup> = -2B/3M</span> so there is a first-order transition rather than a continuous transition.</p>

						<p>It is assumed that in the S phase one-dimensional herringbone order arises at the S/R<sub>I</sub> boundary.  If we examine the <span class="equation">φ</span> dependent terms in Equation 2 we arrive at the following,</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 4)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Fφ<sup>2</sup> + Gφ<sup>4</sup> + |U|φ<sup>2</sup>ξ - |H|φh<sup>2</sup></p>
						</div>

						<p>where the signs of <span class="equation">U</span> and <span class="equation">H</span> depend on the arguments in the cosine terms, which will be determined below.</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 5)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= (F - |U|ξ - |H|h) φ<sup>2</sup> + Gφ<sup>4</sup> = F’φ<sup>2</sup> + Gφ<sup>4</sup></p>
						</div>

						<p>When <span class="equation">F’</span> changes sign there is a 2<sup>nd</sup> order transition from a phase (R<sub>I</sub>) in which <span class="equation">φ=0</span> to a phase (S) in <span class="equation">φ=(-F/2G)<sup>½</sup></span>.</p>

						<p>The tile-dependent terms in Equation 2</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 6)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Aη<sup>2</sup> + Bη<sup>4</sup> +	Jφ<sup>2</sup>η<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – δ) – Vξη<sup>2</sup> cos 2(ω – β)</p>
						</div>

						<p>determine the location of the S/L<sub>2</sub>′ transition.  Collecting the terms gives</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 7)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= [A + Bη<sup>2</sup> + Jφ<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – δ) – Vξ cos 2(β – ω)]η<sup>2</sup> + Bη<sup>4</sup></p>
						</div>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 8)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= A″η<sup>2</sup> + Bη<sup>4</sup></p>
						</div>

						<p>So, again, there is a 2nd order transition when <span class="equation">A″=0</span>.  Note that this is not the point at which the R<sub>II</sub>/Ov transition occurs because <span class="equation">A≠A″</span>.</p>

						<p>It is observed from GID studies that the herringbone order direction is perpendicular to the tilt direction <span class="equation">β – δ = π/2</span> and </p>

						<p><span class="equation">-Hφ<sup>2</sup>h cos 6(γ – δ) = Hφ<sup>2</sup>h cos 6(β – γ)</span></p>

						<p>The transition from L<sub>2</sub>′ to L<sub>2h</sub> is then controlled by the two terms</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 9)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Hφ<sup>2</sup>hcos 6(β – γ) – Dhη<sup>6</sup> cos 6(β – γ) = (Hφ<sup>2</sup> – Dη<sup>6</sup>) h cos 6(β – γ)</p>
						</div>

						<p>and the transition therefore occurs on the line</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 10)</p>
							<p>Hφ<sup>2</sup> – Dη<sup>6</sup> = 0</p>
						</div>

						<p>The distortion in the L<sub>2h</sub> phase is connected to both tilt and the herringbone order.  Consider the terms in the free energy involving <span class="equation">ξ</span>:</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 11)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Cξ<sup>2</sup> – Uφ<sup>2</sup>ξ cos 2(ω – δ) – Vξη<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – ω) =  Cξ<sup>2</sup> + (Uφ<sup>2</sup> - Vη<sup>2</sup>) ξ cos 2(β – ω) </p>
						</div>

						<p>Here we have used the relation between <span class="equation">β</span> and <span class="equation">δ</span> given above.  From the previous analysis we <span class="equation">C&gt;0</span>, <span class="equation">U&gt;0</span>, and <span class="equation">V&gt;0</span> so the relation between <span class="equation">β</span> and <span class="equation">ω</span> is determined be the sign of the term in parentheses.  At small tilt angles the term <span class="equation">Uφ<sup>2</sup></span> dominates and <span class="equation">β – ω = π/2</span>, while at larger values of <span class="equation">η</span> the term in parentheses is negative and the free energy is minimized by <span class="equation">β = ω</span>, thus the transition from distortion perpendicular to the tilt direction to distortion parallel to the tilt direction occurs at</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 12)</p>
							<p>Uφ<sup>2</sup> - Vη<sup>2</sup> = 0</p>
						</div>

						<p>At which point the cell is hexagonal (undistorted).  This occurs at a value of the tilt order parameter <span class="equation">η<sub>0</sub> = (U/V)<sup>½</sup>φ</span>.</p>

						<p>A consequence of Equations 10 and 11 is the requirement that both the L<sub>2</sub>′/L<sub>2</sub> transition lines and the zero-distortion lines end at <span class="equation">φ=0</span> and <span class="equation">η=0</span> which for example is at the intersection of the LS/R<sub>I</sub> line with the tilted-untilted transition line.</p>

						<p>So far, we have treated the R<sub>I</sub> phase as having no distortion, but this phase, which was identified by GID measurements on heneicosanoic acid, has a distorted hexagonal structure.  The origin of this distortion is not clear.  If, as Kaganer and collaborators argue, the herringbone order first appears in the S phase, the distortion in the R<sub>I</sub> phase cannot be attributed to herringbone order.</p>

						<p>BAM studies of the tilting transition from the LS phase show that it is first order at low temperature and second order at high temperature.  An explanation for this change is that the first-order transitions occur from the R<sub>I</sub> phase.  We can examine this possibility by determining the effect of distortion on the tilting transition when there is no herringbone order.  This possibility has been discussed by Kaganer and Indenboom.</p>

						<p>Following them, we consider the effect of higher-order terms in the tilt-distortion coupling and write the free energy</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 13)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Aη<sup>2</sup> + Bη<sup>4</sup> – Vξη<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – ω) + Kξ<sup>2</sup>η<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β + 2ω) + Lξη<sup>4</sup> cos 2(2β + ω ) – Dη<sup>6</sup> cos 6(β) + Cξ<sup>2</sup></p>
						</div>

						<p>The 4<sup>th</sup> and 5<sup>th</sup> terms are the next highest order terms in <span class="equation">Φ<sub>ηξ</sub></span>, Equation 2.  To simplify the notation we have omitted the coupling to the hexatic order, which plays no role and truncated at <span class="equation">η<sup>6</sup></span>.</p>

						<p>To analyze Equation 13 we determine <span class="equation">ξ</span> to lowest order by minimizing the free energy</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 14)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Φ<sub>ξ</sub> + Φ<sub>ξη</sub> = Cξ<sup>2</sup> - Vξη<sup>2</sup> cos 2(β – ω)</p>
						</div>

						<p>which gives</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 15)</p>
							<p>ξ = ( Vη<sup>2</sup> / 2C ) cos 2(β – ω)</p>
						</div>

						<p>If <span class="equation">C&gt;0</span> and <span class="equation">V&gt;0</span>, as we have found in the earlier analyses, <span class="equation">β – ω = 0</span> and the distortion is in the tilt direction.</p>

						<p>Inserting Equation 15 into Equation 13 gives:</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 16)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Aη<sup>2</sup> + Bη<sup>4</sup> – (V<sup>2</sup> / 2C)η<sup>4</sup> + (KV<sup>2</sup>η<sup>6</sup> / 4C<sup>2</sup>) cos 6β + (LVη<sup>4</sup> / 2C) cos 6β – Dη<sup>6</sup> cos 6β</p>
						</div>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 17)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Aη<sup>2</sup> + [B – (V<sup>2</sup> / 2C)]η<sup>4</sup> – [D + (KV<sup>2</sup> / 4C<sup>2</sup>) + (LV / 2C)]η<sup>6</sup> cos 6β</p>
						</div>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 18)</p>
							<p>Φ 	= Aη<sup>2</sup> + B’η<sup>4</sup> – D’η<sup>6</sup> cos 6β</p>
						</div>

						<p>Where <span class="equation">B’ = B – V<sup>2</sup>/2C</span> and <span class="equation">D’=D – KV<sup>2</sup>/4C<sup>2</sup> – LV/2C</span></p>

						<p>The effect of the distortion is to renormalize the coefficients <span class="equation">B</span> and <span class="equation">D</span>.  There would be a similar renormalization in <span class="equation">ξ</span> and <span class="equation">η</span>.  The renormalization opens the possibility of <span class="equation">B&lt;0</span>, which could change the tilt transition to 1<sup>st</sup> order.  In that case, as discussed, it is necessary for stability that the coefficient of the <span class="equation">η<sup>6</sup></span> term be positive and we should also include the term <span class="equation">Mη<sup>6</sup></span> in the expansion as in Equation 1.  This gives then that the 6<sup>th</sup> order terms are <span class="equation">(M – D’ cos 6β)η<sup>6</sup></span> with the requirement that <span class="equation">(M – D’ cos 6β) &gt; 0</span>.  For NN tilt <span class="equation">β=0</span> and for NNN <span class="equation">β=π/6</span>.</p>

						<p>So if</p>

						<p><span class="equation">D&lt;0, M&gt;0	M – D’ cos 6β &gt; 0	NN tilt</span></p>
						<p><span class="equation">D&gt;0, M&gt;0	M – D’ cos 6β &gt; 0	NNN tilt</span></p>

						<p>This is the opposite of the case when there is no distortion and the transition is 2<sup>nd</sup> order.</p>

					</div>

					<div id="AFtemperatureAndPressureDependenceOfPhaseBoundaries" class="section">
						<h3>Temperature and Pressure Dependence of Phase Boundaries</h3>
						<p>In light of the preceding analysis of the various contributions to the free energy and the stability of the phases, we can construct a schematic phase diagram, <a href="#figVII-4">Figure VII-4</a>.</p>

						<div class="figure" id="figVII-4">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure VII-4	Schematic phase diagram after analysis." href="img/dissertation/sketchOfPhaseBoundaries2.png"><img src="img/dissertation/sketchOfPhaseBoundaries2.png" alt="Figure VII-4	Schematic phase diagram after analysis." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure VII-4	Schematic phase diagram after analysis.</p>
						</div>

						<p>The L<sub>2</sub> phase is shown separated by the <span class="equation">φ=0</span> line into 2 regions, L<sub>2h</sub> in which there is herringbone order and L<sub>2d</sub> in which there is not.  The boundaries on the diagram correspond to the changes in sign of various parameters of combinations of parameters.  In order to locate them in the π – T diagram it is necessary to deduce or make some assumptions about their pressure and temperature dependence.  It seems reasonable, but it is by no means certain, that we can treat the molecular tilt, and therefore <span class="equation">η<sup>2</sup></span>, as a function only of π and the herringbone order as a function only of T.</p>
					</div>

					<div id="AFconclusion" class="section">
						<h3>Conclusion</h3>
						<p>We have shown the topology of the phase diagram from analysis but to locate the boundaries in π-T space we need to have a model for the relation between the coefficients and the experimental variables.  This to date has not been done.  However, the analytical phase diagram already bears some resemblance to the Type I and Type II diagrams that we have seen experimentally.  For example in Type II diagrams, there is evidence for the separation of the L<sub>2</sub>′/Ov region into two regions.  However in Type I diagrams, there is no evidence of a split of the L<sub>2</sub> phase into L<sub>2h</sub> and L<sub>2d</sub>.  The only experimental evidence for any backbone order is in the X-Ray work of Dutta [<a href="#ref29">29</a>] which shows from the appearance of extra peaks in heneicosanoic acid that it does exist in the CS and L<sub>2</sub>″ phases.</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div id="domainKineticsStudiedByImageAnalysisOfBrewsterAngleMicroscopyData" class="section">
					<h3>VIII. - Domain Kinetics Studied by Image Analysis of Brewster-angle Microscopy Data</h3>
					<div id="DKintroduction" class="section">
						<h3>Introduction</h3>
						<p>Langmuir monolayers of the compounds studied in this work, <a href="#tableVII-A">Table VII-A</a>, all form mosaic-like textures upon initial deposition or upon decompression from the untilted phases to the tilted phases.  These textures can readily be imaged using Brewster-angle microscopy.  These textures are the result of azimuthal tilt variations.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figVIII-1">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure VIII-1	Mosaic texture ..." href="img/dissertation/mosaicTiltDomains.png"><img src="img/dissertation/mosaicTiltDomains.png" alt="Figure VIII-1	Mosaic texture (left) of a typical Langmuir monolayer with azimuthal tilt directors schematically represented (right)." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure VIII-1	Mosaic texture (left) of a typical Langmuir monolayer with azimuthal tilt directors schematically represented (right).</p>
						</div>
						<p>Over time, these textures anneal or ripen to form, at first approximation, the same textures at a larger length scales.  This behavior is reminiscent of other 2-D growth processes in metallurgy [<a href="#ref30">30</a>] and surface science [<a href="#ref31">31</a>,<a href="#ref32">32</a>,<a href="#ref33">33</a>].  In general, as these textures develop over very long times they become stripe-like or develop arrangements that are more complex.  Qualitative observations from seconds to a few days have been made, such as; amphiphiles with short chains anneal faster, those with longer chains at long times tend to form irregular shapes, and anisotropy develops with time.  However, techniques to provide quantified values have not been available.  Because the molecules in these monolayer systems cannot move out of the 2-D plane at an appreciable rate it is expected that this system will provide an excellent basis for 2-D kinetic modeling of a non-conserved order parameter with several ground states.  It is our desire to study the kinetic process and determine which parameters influence growth, what existing growth laws apply, and what the final equilibrium states may be.</p>
						<p>The focus of this study has been to develop methods to quantify these values and then in turn provide results for the rate of growth dependence at different quench depths.  At this point, we have explored reproducibility and the effect of annealing time in the untilted phase at a single quench depth, and can make qualitative statements about different quench depths.  These are the first measurements of this kind and are preliminary due to the difficulty in developing a suitable image analysis technique.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="DKtheoryOfDomainGrowth" class="section">
						<h3>Theory of Domain Growth</h3>

						<p>Quenched systems are typically modeled using continuum Landau-Ginzburg or Cahn-Hilliard type equations [<a href="#ref34">34</a>].  It has been shown that for systems with a single order parameter and a ground state degeneracy of two (<span class="equation">Q=2</span>, two types of domains) that the average domain length scales with time as <span class="equation">t<sup>n</sup></span>, where <span class="equation">n</span> is the domain-growth exponent, while the distribution of sizes remains the same.  For systems with a non-conserved order parameter (Model A) this exponent has been shown to be <span class="equation">n=1/2</span> [<a href="#ref35">35</a>,<a href="#ref36">36</a>].  For systems with a conserved order parameter (Model B) this exponent has been shown to be <span class="equation">n=1/3</span> [<a href="#ref37">37</a>].  Model A systems are driven by minimizing domain boundary curvature.  A typical example of a Model A system is a single component quenched into a two-phase co-existence region.  Typically, long-range interactions are not considered.  Model B systems are driven by diffusive growth.  An example is the phase separation of a binary mixture.</p>
						<p>Using BAM, one can visualize monolayer domains, which are differentiated by azimuthal tilt regions.  Azimuthal tilt is non-conserved.  Let us consider monolayer systems of long chain lengths formed by the compounds in <a href="#tableVII-A">Table VII-A</a>.  If the single dominant order parameter is azimuthal tilt and there are no dominant long-range interactions such as dipolar interactions, these systems should behave like Model A for <span class="equation">Q=2</span>.  However, these systems have six ground states, <span class="equation">Q=6</span>.  Not much was known until recently about systems with more than two ground states, although Liftshitz [<a href="#ref38">38</a>] predicted a slowing, or about systems with more than two order parameters.  Later, Safran [<a href="#ref39">39</a>] argued that a system with <span class="equation">Q=d+1</span>, where <span class="equation">d</span> is the number of spatial dimensions or two in this case, could become pinned or trapped in local metastable states that would greatly slow the kinetics.</p>
						<p>Calculations for <span class="equation">Q=2</span> (the Ising model) use a simple Hamiltonian, where <span class="equation">σ</span> is zero or one and <span class="equation">J</span> is the spin energy summed over all pairs of nearest neighbors.  Parallel spins are favored (<span class="equation">-J, J>0</span>) and antiparallel spins are discouraged (<span class="equation">+J</span>).</p>
								(Ising Hamiltonian, no external field)
						<p>A generalized model for <span class="equation">Q>2</span> was developed by Potts in 1952,</p>
								(Potts Hamiltonian)
						<p>where <span class="equation">σ<sub>i</sub></span> is the <span class="equation">Q</span> state of the spin on site <span class="equation">i</span> (<span class="equation">1= σ<sub>i</sub> =Q</span>) and <span class="equation">δ<sub>i,j</sub></span> is the Kronecker delta function.  The sum is taken over all nearest-neighbor spins and <span class="equation">J>0</span>.</p>
						<p>It is possible that with these monolayer systems the spin-spin interaction energy <span class="equation">J</span> is dependent on the value of the spins, resulting in anisotropic line energies.  As an example, one can imagine that the line energy between two domains of similar azimuthal tilt is lower than the line energy between two domains of opposite tilt.  Some evidence for this has been observed in experiments by noting that after annealing, domains of opposite tilt tend not to be neighbors.  In this case, a modified Potts model could be used where <span class="equation">J</span> is a function of the spin-spin values <span class="equation">i,j</span>.</p>
						<p>Recent computer simulations have predicted a variety of exponents for systems of <span class="equation">Q>2</span>.  Seigert [<a href="#ref40">40</a>] predicted that for a conserved order parameter with two components an exponent of 1/4.  Using Monte Carlo simulations Anderson [<a href="#ref41">41</a>] determined that the exponent decreases linearly between <span class="equation">2=Q=30</span> to a constant near 0.41 for <span class="equation">Q>30</span>.  Simulations by Grest [<a href="#ref42">42</a>] and Enomoto [<a href="#ref43">43</a>]  determined that for <span class="equation">2=Q=8</span> the exponent is 1/2.  Chen [<a href="#ref44">44</a>] found an exponent of 1/2 for a system with many non-conserved order parameters.</p>
						<p>Dr. Yi Jiang of the Los Alamos National Laboratory conducted preliminary simulations of a modified 6-state Potts model at our request where <span class="equation">J</span> is dependent on the spins values.  This seemed to be a reasonable simulation of our system since there are 6 tilt directions.  The interface energy was defined as <span class="equation">E = 1 - cos (dF)</span>, where <span class="equation">dF</span> is the difference between two neighboring azimuthal tilt angles.  The Monte Carlo Simulation used a 128x128 lattice size, a temperature of zero, ~2500 steps, and a uniform random distribution of 6 states (π/3, 2π/3, 3π/3, 4π/3, 5π/3, 6π/3).  Dr. Yi Jiang found an exponent of <span class="equation">n=0.49</span> or nearly 1/2, <a href="#figVIII-2">Figure VIII-2</a>.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figVIII-2">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure VIII-2	Monte Carlo results ..." href="img/dissertation/plotOfPottsSimulationFromYiJiang_edges4.GIF"><img src="img/dissertation/plotOfPottsSimulationFromYiJiang_edges4.GIF" alt="Figure VIII-2	Monte Carlo results from a modified 6-state Potts model." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure VIII-2	Monte Carlo results from a modified 6-state Potts model.</p>
						</div>
						<p>Since these monolayer systems often form stripes at very long times it is possible the growth dynamics would be governed by a Smith-Hohenberg type equation which gives an exponent of 0.20-0.25 for late times.  This equation describes coarsening from a disordered phase to a striped phase for a non-conserved order parameter and it has successfully been applied to Rayleigh-Benard convective rolls.  The 1/4 value is associated with defect pinning.  A recent paper by Boyer and Vinals [<a href="#ref45">45</a>] looked at early times and found the exponent 1/3, which is associated with domain boundary motion.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="DKtheoryOfImageProcessing" class="section">
						<h3>Theory of Image Processing</h3>
						<p>To facilitate automated processing of the large amount of data necessary to generate useful statistics, a series of image-processing algorithms or steps have been developed that are focused on preserving the domain's adjacency, area, shape, and type while removing artifacts such as noise and blur.  The software implementation of these algorithms takes a given measured image and produces a reconstructed piecewise-smooth ‘real’ image, which is in turn quantized into a non-gradiated sharp-edged image suitable for general analysis.  A denoising-deblurring variational model is used to reconstruct the real image and a classical Lloyd method is used to quantize the image.  The variational method and the implementation of the Lloyd method were developed by Dr. Luminita Vese and Dr. Tony Chan of the UCLA Mathematics Department.</p>

						<p>The assumed degradation model was <span class="equation">u<sub>0</sub> = Ku + η</span>, where <span class="equation">u<sub>0</sub> ≈</span> measured noisy and or blurred image, <span class="equation">u ≈</span> the real reconstructed image, <span class="equation">K</span> = the blur, and <span class="equation">η</span> = the noise.  It was assumed that the blur is constant across the image field.  The blur is actually a function of the distance from the focal line of the BAM.  Close to the focal line the difference in blur is small.  Images were cropped prior to processing to take advantage of this.</p>

						<p>The denoising-deblurring step is conducted by minimizing,</p>

