							<img src="img/dissertation/theoryOfImageProcessing/eqn005.gif" alt="" />
						</div>

						<p>Segmentation and edge finding was conducted by minimizing</p>

						<div class="equation">
							<p class="caption">(Eq. 2)</p>
							<img src="img/dissertation/theoryOfImageProcessing/eqn006.gif" alt="(Eq. 2)" />
						</div>

						<p>where <span class="equation">u<sub>0</sub></span> is the result from Equation 1.  The edge function is calculated by <img src="img/dissertation/theoryOfImageProcessing/eqn007.gif" alt="edge function" />.  For small <span class="equation">&rho;: v ≈ 1</span> (white) in homogeneous regions, <span class="equation">v ≈ 0</span> (black) on edges.</p>

						<p>If <span class="equation">α</span> is large and / or <span class="equation">&rho;</span> is small then diffusion is strong and the amount of edge decreases.  If <span class="equation">α</span> is small and / or <span class="equation">&rho;</span> is not as small, the diffusion is weaker and the solution <span class="equation">u</span> is close to the data <span class="equation">u<sub>0</sub></span> and the amount of edge increases.  These two models are used to remove the noise, while preserving the edges.</p>

						<p>Finally, to quantize the image we define the quantizer separators and quantizers as follows:</p>
						<p><span class="equation">t<sub>1</sub>, t<sub>2</sub>, …, t<sub>N+1</sub></span> (quantizer separators),</p>
						<p><span class="equation">u<sub>1</sub>, u<sub>2</sub>, …, u<sub>N</sub></span> (quantizers), with</p>
