						<p>If initially <span class="equation">u(i,j) &#206; [t<sub>k</sub>, t<sub>k+1</sub>)</span>, then replace <span class="equation">u(i,j)</span> by <span class="equation">u<sub>k</sub></span>.</p>
						<p>The classical method (Lloyd) is used to minimize the average quadratic error.  Let <span class="equation">H(s)</span> be the probability distribution of <span class="equation">u</span> given by <img src="img/dissertation/theoryOfImageProcessing/eqn008.gif" alt="edge function" /> and minimize the energy <img src="img/dissertation/theoryOfImageProcessing/eqn009.gif" alt="" /></p>
					</div>
					<div id="DKbamExperiment" class="section">
						<h3>BAM Experiment</h3>
						<p>The experiment was conducted by compressing a monolayer of n-nonadecanol (C19OH) into the R<sub>II</sub> region of the LS phase at ~17mN/m and ~20°C, annealing for 5-10min, quenching to ~9.0 mN/m in the L<sub>2</sub>′/Ov phase, and observing the texture periodically.  Other quench depths were qualitatively observed.  Images at shallow depths within 1 mN/m of the untilted line were difficult to process because of the lack of contrast near the transition line.  Deeper quenches appeared to anneal faster at early times.</p>
						<p>An alcohol was used because of its small non-complex head group.  The chain length was chosen such that the quench line was at room temperature and the untilted and tilted phases were not a restricted rotator or a herringbone ordered phase respectively.  Room temperature quenches allowed for easier measurements and a minimal thermal gradient between the trough and the air.  Large gradients would significantly increase flow.  The R<sub>II</sub> region of the LS phase is a rotator phase and lacks herringbone order.  It is likely to exhibit fewer memory effects and shorter annealing times.  In addition, it was necessary to choose a chain length that exhibited a texture with distinct domain types.  Shorter chain lengths result in domains that have slowly varying reflectivity due to bend and/or splay.  Longer chain lengths, greater than 17 methylene units for n-alkanol, result in a fixed number of reflectivities within one field of view, six for n-nonadecanol.</p>
						<p>The uncertainty in time-zero was ~1.5 seconds or the time it took to perform a quench.  Faster quenching was achieved but not used due to the tearing and excessive short-term flow that occurred.  It was achieved by unmounting the barrier from the motor and using a tension spring or band to rapidly move the barrier.  A stop device was then employed to arrest the barrier at the correct thermodynamic coordinate.</p>
						<p>Monolayer flow was reduced but not eliminated by the use of airflow barriers around the trough and a glass ring, approximately 5cm in diameter, under the monolayer surface.  The water sub-phase was brought to a level just above the edge of the glass ring.  The imaging laser spot was aligned to an area within the surface enclosed by the ring.  The majority of the remaining flow was due to local heating by the laser.  The flow was maintained below 10μm/s.  Slow rotation was visible but less than 0.25°/minute.</p>
						<p>An upper limit was imposed on the observation time by contaminants that introduced themselves into the system through the air.  Altered phase behavior was apparent after ~36 hours and substantial property loss, such as the loss of the tilted phases entirely, occurred at ~96 hours.   For observation times greater than 36 hours, it would be necessary to seal the system.  As an experiment, a cover glass was used to partially seal the system.  The cover glass was 0.7mm thick coated by indium-tin oxide and heated by two brass electrodes epoxied to the surface (Delta Technologies).  This reduced contamination but local heating of the cover glass by the laser and heating elements resulted in large scale slowly varying imaging artifacts.  In addition, the temperature gradient imposed by the cover glass created flow in the layer, likely leading to altered growth dynamics and problems maintaining a fixed field of view.</p>
						<p>Annealing times less than 1 minute resulted in domain distributions that were influenced by the state of the distribution prior to compression into the untilted phases, a memory of the previous texture.  This was indicated by large initial domain sizes or remaining vestiges of a previous pattern and structure such as stripes. </p>
						<p>The Brewster-angle microscope used has been described previously [<a href="#ref49">49</a>].  In addition, an intracavity aperture was installed in the laser to assure a gaussian mode (TEM00).  Images formed by the objective were collected using a charge-coupled device (CCD) camera (Dage-MTI Inc., model CCD-72S). The camera's IR filter was removed and the sensitivity was 0.08 lux. The camera's photo response curve was shown to be s-shaped. The output signal has a sigmodial shape and is linear to the illumination from 20-80% of the saturation level. The camera was operated in a fixed gain mode and was gated by a time-based integrator (Dage-MTI Inc., model Investigater).  The time-based integrator was set to video frame rates other than 30s<sup>-1</sup>. Typical rates were 7.5s<sup>-1</sup> (factor 2) and 3.75s<sup>-1</sup> (factor 1).</p>
						<p>The video signal generated by the camera was passed through a time base corrector, time stamp generator, and then recorded with a videocassette recorder (VCR).  After an experiment the tape was replayed and images were digitally captured using a computer video capture card (Data Translation, model DT3155) at specific intervals using 1-byte pixels.  The time base corrector (Hotronics Inc., model AP41) synchronized the image with the video card and helped free the image from distortion or noise bands.  The videocassette recorder was operated in SP SVHS mode and was equipped with a digital frame buffer for playback.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figVIII-3">
							<img src="img/dissertation/" alt="Figure VIII-3	Captured images at times 12s, 36s, 1m, 1m40s, 3m20s, 5m (left to right then top to bottom).  The field of view is not distortion corrected for the BAM viewing angle and is 200μm wide.  The focal line is left to right." />
							<p class="caption">Figure VIII-3	Captured images at times 12s, 36s, 1m, 1m40s, 3m20s, 5m (left to right then top to bottom).  The field of view is not distortion corrected for the BAM viewing angle and is 200μm wide.  The focal line is left to right.</p>
						</div>
						<p>A typical sequence of captured images is shown in <a href="#figVIII-3">Figure VIII-3</a>.  This sequence represents an experiment conducted with a fixed field of view.  In fixed field experiments, the trough was manually moved during the experiment to compensate for flow and to maintain the same point under the microscope objective.  Preliminary experiments with times exceeding a few hours were conducted where the monolayer was allowed to wander under the field of view.  These experiments were initially unsuccessful because of the pronounced regional inhomogeneity of domain sizes.  Domains within a millimeter of each other tend to be in the same regional group where the average size is strongly correlated.  Domains of differing region groups have different average sizes to within an order of magnitude.  Sampling different regional groups over short times (&lt;10 hours) resulted in poor statistics.  Multiple experiments under the same conditions or very long experiments with a sealed system could be conducted to recover these statistics.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="DKimageProcessing" class="section">
						<h3>Image Processing</h3>
						<p>Calculations centered on determining an exponent for the domain area rate of growth.  However, addition information could be extracted from the results including domain-domain correlations, line shape, and anisotropy as a function of time.  To calculate the domain-domain correlations it would be necessary to correct the image to visualize domains with different azimuthal tilts that appear the same.  These domains can appear the same at certain orientations under a BAM due to the form of the reflectivity response function.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figVIII-4">
							<img src="img/dissertation/" alt="Figure VIII-4	Theoretical reflectivity response function for n-nonadecanol (tilt 20°, wavelength 514nm, dielectric permeability 2.31, and delta dielectric 0.12).  The function was derived by C. Lautz et al. and Th. M. Fischer [50,51]" />
							<p class="caption">Figure VIII-4	Theoretical reflectivity response function for n-nonadecanol (tilt 20°, wavelength 514nm, dielectric permeability 2.31, and delta dielectric 0.12).  The function was derived by C. Lautz et al. and Th. M. Fischer [<a href="#ref50">50</a>,<a href="#ref51">51</a>]</p>
						</div>
						<p>A correction could be made by mapping the reconstructed image to an ‘azimuthal’ image using the mapping function shown in <a href="#figVIII-4">Figure VIII-4</a>.</p>
						<p>Generally, images were corrected for the BAM viewing angle, however in the absence of shape anisotropy (short times) and field rotation (short times) it was not necessary.  The processing algorithms are sensitive to the local image gradient that is in turn a function of the image brightness and contrast.  It is essential to maintain a constant image brightness and contrast over the duration of the experiment.  Long-time variations were removed by operating the laser in constant power mode and maintaining thermal constancy of the imaging and optical components.  Short-time variations such as those caused by vibration were removed by frame averaging.  Note that if too much frame averaging is used, blurring and loss of detail around domain-domain edges resulted, especially for early times.  This was due to the flow of the monolayer.  Field rotation is also problematic because it varies the relative contrasts of the domains to each other and thus the sensitivity of the algorithms over time.  It should be noted that at very long times (~36 hours), just before measurable phase behavior change, a slow partial loss of contrast in the monolayer was apparent presumably due to airborne contaminants.</p>
						<p>Due to the spot illumination of the laser and optical artifacts, illumination of the field of view was not uniform or ‘flat’.  To flatten the field a clean water surface was imaged.  This image was then scaled and subtracted from a captured image to perform a background subtraction.  This ratio was not one for two reasons.  The water surface has a different reflectivity than the monolayer and the water surface exhibited more vibrations than a monolayer covered surface requiring a longer integration time that resulted in an overall greater brightness.</p>
						<p>Adjustable parameters were chosen to match a given experimental setup.  Parameter values were used that selected domains that corresponded to what a human observer would choose as a domain and made constant for all images captured in one experiment.  In practice, it was rarely necessary to change parameters from one experiment to the next if the optics, digital electronics, and laser power were not changed.  The parameters values include <span class="equation">r<sub>sub</sub></span> (background subtraction ratio), <span class="equation">α</span> (regularizing parameter), <span class="equation">&rho;</span> (edge function parameter), <span class="equation">R</span> (blur radius), <span class="equation">u<sub>N</sub></span> (the number of quantizers, domain reflectivities, or colors), <span class="equation">min/max</span> (minimum and maximum values before divergence), <span class="equation">mesh</span> (mesh step size), and <span class="equation">i</span> (number of iterations necessary to achieve a stepwise smooth result) (see Eq.1 and Eq.2).  The <span class="equation">min/max</span> values are limits in the denoising-deblurring step before a point is considered diverged.  The <span class="equation">mesh</span> step size represents how many pixels form a point.  The processing algorithms extended the edges of the image by reflection for calculations that required a continuous edge.</p>
						<div class="figure" id="figVIII-5">
							<img src="img/dissertation/" alt="Figure VIII-5	Results from a typical processing run at early time (top) and late time (bottom).  The left image is after background subtraction.  The center image is the denoise-deblurred image with edges marked in black.  The right image is the quantized image." />
							<p class="caption">Figure VIII-5	Results from a typical processing run at early time (top) and late time (bottom).  The left image is after background subtraction.  The center image is the denoise-deblurred image with edges marked in black.  The right image is the quantized image.</p>
						</div>
						<p>All processing steps take ~7 minutes per image on a 400MHz Pentium II processor using Sun Microsystem's v1.2 Java Virtual Machine.  A limited number of captures were processed.</p>
						<p>Values for the parameters were set by trial and error.  The blur was chosen such that it was no larger than the smallest domain size after 1.5 seconds and was close to the step width between two domains. The following values were typical.</p>


						<div class="table" id="tableVIII-A">
