						<p>Although a constant blur operator was used, it is possible to determine the form of a non-constant operator by using an image with a constant repeating texture.  This would allow for the use of a greater field of view.  As an example, we selected an image of vertical stripes with the focal plane in the horizontal direction, <a href="#figVIII-6">Figure VIII-6</a>.</p>
						<p>If we take a cross sections at values along the y-axis, measure the step distance across the domain boundaries for all boundaries in a cross section, average those values, and then plot the average value vs. the location of the cross section along the y-axis, one can see the functional form of the blur along the y-axis, <a href="#figVIII-7">Figure VIII-7</a>.</p>
