					<div id="DKresults" class="section">
						<h3>Results</h3>
						<p>Several experiments were conducted over a period of approximately 7 minutes each.  The same optics and sequence of digital electronics were used in each experiment.  Captured images were sampled at higher frequencies during the first 3 minutes of playback (~1 img/ 3 seconds) andlower frequencies (~1 img/ 10-20 seconds) during the remaining time.  Each image was processed first by cropping, background subtraction, denoising-deblurring, edge finding, and then quantization using the parameters outlined in <a href="#tableVIII-A">Table VIII-A</a>.  Except for cropping, each processing step was performed by a custom image-processing program (IP).  The processing algorithms were originally coded independently in Fortran by Dr. Luminita Vese of the UCLA Mathematics Department and then ported to Java to form an integrated program.  The port was conducted to facilitate batch processing, multithreading, and to add a graphical user interface.</p>
