					<div id="DKconclusion" class="section">
						<h3>Conclusion</h3>
						<p>If the average domain length scales as <span class="equation">t<sup>n</sup></span> we find that <span class="equation">n=0.246</span> or very close to 1/4.</p>
						<p>A value of <span class="equation">n=1/2</span> might have be have been anticipated based on the work by Grest [<a href="#ref42">42</a>] and Enomoto [<a href="#ref43">43</a>] for systems of <span class="equation">2=Q=8</span> where he showed <span class="equation">n=1/2</span>, the work by Anderson [<a href="#ref41">41</a>] for systems where <span class="equation">2=Q=30</span> where the value of <span class="equation">n</span> was <span class="equation">0.50=n&lt;0.41</span>, or the 6-state Potts model simulation conducted by Dr. Yi Jiang which also showed <span class="equation">n=1/2</span>.</p>
						<p>The result of <span class="equation">n=1/4</span> is consistent with late time Rayleigh-Benard coarsening.  Although the data was taken over a relatively short time, some anisotropy was apparent in the domain structures by examining the Fourier transforms of the BAM images prior to processing.  However, at the longest times observable the system developed a texture that can be described as a long irregular jagged area rather than the smooth stripes seen in other shorter chain length compounds.</p>
						<p>A number of other order parameters may be present in these systems, such as head group domains and dipolar interactions.  However, initial results are consistent with a system with a non-conserved order parameter coarsening from a disordered phase to a striped phase.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div id="appendixUseOfImageProcessingSoftware" class="section">
					<h3>IX - Appendix: Use of Image Processing Software</h3>
					<div id="IPgeneral" class="section">
						<h3>General</h3>
						<p>The image processing software was ported from several Fortran programs to a single program in Java called the Image Processor (IP).  IP was developed using the Java2 language, version 1.2 and 1.3.  The code is available for download at <a href="http://www.ellisteer.com/">http://www.ellisteer.com/</a> and is currently at version 3.0.1.</p>

						<div class="figure" id="figIX-1">
							<a rel="gallery" title="Figure IX-1 Screen shot of the IP program ..." href="img/dissertation/mainScreenIPScreenShot2.png"><img width="50%" height="50%" src="img/dissertation/mainScreenIPScreenShot2.png" alt="Figure IX-1 Screen shot of the IP program generating a sequence of processed images." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure IX-1 Screen shot of the IP program generating a sequence of processed images.</p>
						</div>

						<p>The graphical user interface is split into three sections and a menu, <a href="#figIX-1">Figure IX-1</a>.</p>

						<p>The menu, top, contains the File, Set, Process, Batch, and Log Menus.  The File Menu is used for setting the working directory, saving image results, and saving log files.  The Set Menu is used to set the parameters used for each single-step and multi-step processing routines.  The Process Menu is used to conduct single-step processing routines.  The Batch Menu is used to conduct multi-step processing routines.  And the Log Menu, which has only one item, is used to clear the current log.</p>

						<p>The file list, top left section, contains a listing of the graphic files in the working directory.  Only.gif and .jpg files can be read and displayed by IP.  Once a directory is selected, a user can click on an entry in the file list.  Selecting an entry starts a new image processing sequence and displays the image on the image stack to the right.  Multiple entries for batch processing can be selected using a combination of the shift and/or control keys.  If the result of a previous operation was not saved, the user will be prompted to confirm the new selection.</p>

						<p>The image stack, top right section, is used for image display.  When a new image is generated because of processing the result image is placed on the stack to the right of the original image.  The result image then becomes the new working image.  Single-step processing operations are always conducted on the working image.</p>

						<p>The log window, bottom section, contains text message results, information, and errors sent by the program.  This is especially useful for capturing the results of a batch-processing run.  A few processing operations such as Color-Quantization result in only text output and do not create a new working image.  Messages in the log are prefixed with &gt;&gt;&gt;, ---, or !!!.  These prefixes represent a message of type result, information, and error respectively.  For example when denoising or denoising-debluring an image a typical error is !!! Denoise-Deblu Error: An Exception occurred. java.lang.ArithmeticException: Alpha is too small.  This indicates a divergence exceeding the min/max boundaries and that the alpha parameter value should be increased.</p>

						<p>The single-step processing routines available are Image-Information, Rescale, Background-Subtract, Denoise, Denoise-Deblur, Edge-Find, and Color-Quantization.  Each single-step routine acts on the working image shown in the image stack.  To process an image; set the parameter values for the routine using the Set menu, make the image to process the working image, and then select the routine name on the Process Menu to begin.  Single-step routines operate on the working image.  If more than one image is selected in the file list only the first image in that list is processed.</p>

						<p>Two multi-step processing routines are available. They are BAM Converter v1.0 and BAM Converter 2.0.  Multi-step processing takes an image and applies several single-step routines in a pre-defined order.  The text results are captured in the log and the final image in the sequence is automatically saved to the current working directory.  To multi-step process an image; set the parameter values using the Set Menu for each processing routine used by the multi-step routine, set the parameter value for the multi-step processing routine itself using the Set Menu, make the image to process the working image, and then select the routine name on the Batch Menu to begin processing.</p>

						<p>Batch processing on multiple images is possible when using multi-step processing routines.  This is done by performing the same actions necessary to multi-step process an image but first selecting multiple entries in the file list.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="IPsettingProcessingParameters" class="section">
						<h3>Setting Processing Parameters</h3>
						<p>Each item on the Set Menu represents a group of parameters, shown together in a dialog box, for each processing routine, <a href="#figIX-2">Figure IX-2</a>.</p>

						<div class="figure" id="figIX-2">
							<a rel="gallery" title="IP Dialog Box" href="img/dissertation/IPDenoisePanel.png"><img src="img/dissertation/IPDenoisePanel.png" alt="Figure IX-2 Screen shots of dialog boxes for setting the parameters of various processing routines." /></a>
							<a rel="gallery" title="IP Dialog Box" href="img/dissertation/IPDenoiseDebluPanel.png"><img src="img/dissertation/IPDenoiseDebluPanel.png" alt="Figure IX-2 Screen shots of dialog boxes for setting the parameters of various processing routines." /></a>
							<a rel="gallery" title="IP Dialog Box" href="img/dissertation/IPEdgeFindPanel.png"><img src="img/dissertation/IPEdgeFindPanel.png" alt="Figure IX-2 Screen shots of dialog boxes for setting the parameters of various processing routines." /></a>
							<p class="caption">Figure IX-2 Screen shots of dialog boxes for setting the parameters of various processing routines.</p>
						</div>

						<p>The Set Menu is shown in two sections separated by a line.  The items above the line separator are parameters for single-step routines.  The items below the line separator are parameters for multi-step routines.  To conduct multi-step processing the parameters for each single-step routine must be set, in addition to the parameters for the multi-step routine itself.  Not all processing routines have settable parameters such as Image-Information and Rescale.  In general, each dialog box has a variables and an options section. The variables are the same as those in <a href="#tableVIII-A">Table VIII-A</a>.  The options generally effect program operation but can also affect the output.  There is a set of default parameters useful for processing BAM images of mosaic-like textures.  These values can be restored using the Restore Defaults button.</p>

					</div>
					<div id="IPsingleStepProcessingRoutineDescriptions" class="section">
						<h3>Single-Step Processing Routine Descriptions</h3>
						<p>In general, each single-step processing routine operates on the magnitude of the pixel values and discards the color information.  For each routine, the image pixels are unpacked into an array of values (64-bit floating-point IEEE754-1985) that is in turn operated on. Each index in the array represents a pixel.  The values are generated by averaging together the red, green, and blue values of each pixel and ignoring any transparency bits.  Once a routine is complete, the array is converted back into pixels using the same value for each color and setting the transparency to zero.  The pixel values for each color are 8-bits.  This requires a truncation of the non-integer portion of the values after processing.  Information on each routine follows.</p>

						<p>The Image-Information routine returns to the log window basic image information including the image dimensions, minimum/maximum/average pixel values, total variation, and total average variation. This routine has no settable parameters.</p>

						<p>Rescale rescales all pixels between 0 and 255. This routine has no settable parameters.</p>

						<p>The Background-Subtract routine takes a preset image scaled by a ratio and subtracts that image from subsequent working images.  The background image is set to the current working image when the Background-Subtract item is selected from the Set Menu.  This image is used for all subsequent subtractions until a new image is set or the program is restarted.</p>

						<p>The Denoise routine uses the same algorithm and settable parameters that the Denoise-Deblur routine uses but does not include the kernel for Deblurring.  The Denoise-Deblur routine includes a non-functioning Auto-Find Alpha option in the parameter dialog box, <a href="#figIX-2">Figure IX-2</a>.  It is possible to iteratively try different values of alpha until the calculation does not diverge to automatically set the alpha parameter.  But since this results in varying values of alpha for each image in a single batch-processing run it was never implemented.</p>

						<p>The Edge-Find routine returns a diffused image with enhancement at the edges.  Optionally, this routine can display the resultant diffused image and/or an image of the edge magnitude detected at each pixel, <a href="#figIX-2">Figure IX-2</a>.  Generally, a user would display only the diffused image to be used by an additional processing routine like Color-Quantization. It is useful to display the diffused image and the edge image to determine how effective the choices of parameters are.</p>

						<p>The Color-Quantization routine returns a quantized image with a number of �colors� or gray values set by a parameter.  The colors are chosen by determining the values of the peaks in the histogram.  Each pixel is remapped to the closest chosen values.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="IPmultiStepProcessingRoutineDescriptions" class="section">
						<h3>Multi-Step Processing Routine Descriptions</h3>
						<p>Multi-step processing routines automatically save the result image.  The saved images are named by appending a suffix to the image name that is set in the parameter dialog box.  For example, when processing a batch of images called test1.gif and test2.gif using the suffix _multi, the saved images would be named test1_multi.gif and test2_multi.gif.</p>

						<p>BAM Image Converter v1.0 applies the following single-step routines in order; Rescale, Background-Subtract, Denoise-Deblur, Edge-Find, and Color-Quantization.  This multi-step routine was used for the image processing throughout this work.</p>

						<p>BAM Image Converter v2.0 applies the following single-step routines in order; Information, Denoise, Rescale, Background-Subtract, Denoise-Deblur, Edge-Find, and Color-Quantization.  This converter is essentially the same as v1.0 except that the image is first denoised.</p>
					</div>
					<div id="IPprogramStructure" class="section">
						<h3>Program Structure</h3>
						<p>In general, code common to single-step routines and general image handling have been placed as static methods in the ImageUtilities object.  This includes methods for loading images, conversion of pixel data, and data reflection.</p>
						<p>Single-step, fast operations, inherit from AbstractFastOp while multi-step, slow operations, inherit from AbstractSlowOp.  Both of these inherit from the common base class AbstractDataOp, which is the abstract superclass of all IP image processing operations.   AbstractSlowOp provides a base implementation of threading and updating facilities needed by slower calculations.</p>
					</div>
				</div>

